00:20:38.780 --> 00:20:41.390
And I fully agree that
citizenship is about more

00:20:41.390 --> 00:20:44.240
than just formal citizenship.

00:20:44.240 --> 00:20:46.610
But I'm not sure
whether the deep emotion

00:20:46.610 --> 00:20:49.640
of feeling at home, the
deep emotion of belonging

00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:54.020
should be part of our
understanding of citizenship.

00:20:54.020 --> 00:20:57.200
Don't get me wrong, it's
important for all of us

00:20:57.200 --> 00:21:00.610
to feel at home somewhere.

00:21:00.610 --> 00:21:05.400
But feeling at home, belonging,
is a very particular emotion.

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:08.480
When you really, truly
feel somewhere at home,

00:21:08.480 --> 00:21:10.810
it often is an
exclusionary emotion.

00:21:10.810 --> 00:21:13.300
It's with some people
at some places.

00:21:13.300 --> 00:21:16.580
And that makes the emotion
as a political emotion very

00:21:16.580 --> 00:21:19.220
difficult. So the
question I will answer

00:21:19.220 --> 00:21:25.090
is, should citizenship be based
on those we feel at home with?

00:21:25.090 --> 00:21:28.160
And that is a difficult
question to answer.

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:30.950
My hesitation or my
skepticism about such

00:21:30.950 --> 00:21:34.910
a more cultural or emotional
definition, sentimental

00:21:34.910 --> 00:21:37.220
definition, of
citizenship is born out

00:21:37.220 --> 00:21:40.340
of my study of my own country,
the Netherlands, which

00:21:40.340 --> 00:21:41.920
I normally would
never speak about.

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:45.020
It is an interesting, small,
tiny, not very important

00:21:45.020 --> 00:21:45.950
country.

00:21:45.950 --> 00:21:47.690
But for today, it is important.

00:21:47.690 --> 00:21:50.330
And I will explain
why it is important.

00:21:50.330 --> 00:21:53.900
Because in this very
particular country,

00:21:53.900 --> 00:21:56.210
politicians-- nor
to public opinion--

00:21:56.210 --> 00:21:59.030
doesn't stop speaking the
language of feeling at home.

00:21:59.030 --> 00:22:01.610
And particularly-- the white
people tell us all the time--

00:22:01.610 --> 00:22:03.590
that they don't
feel at home anymore

00:22:03.590 --> 00:22:06.110
in the country they live in.

00:22:06.110 --> 00:22:08.330
And this new nationalism
that's developed

00:22:08.330 --> 00:22:11.330
is quite puzzling, because
this new nationalism is so much

00:22:11.330 --> 00:22:15.900
based on the idea that we
have to share all our values,

00:22:15.900 --> 00:22:17.600
norms, and feelings.

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:20.540
And to be honest, those
feelings, those norms

00:22:20.540 --> 00:22:22.700
and values, are rather
sympathetic to me

00:22:22.700 --> 00:22:25.160
because they are progressive.

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:28.800
As I will try to show in
the coming 12 minutes,

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:32.180
there might be progress, but
they are, at the same time,

00:22:32.180 --> 00:22:34.340
highly exclusionary
towards those

00:22:34.340 --> 00:22:39.320
we assume do not hear in those
same values and feelings.

00:22:39.320 --> 00:22:42.170
So let me try to explain that.

00:22:42.170 --> 00:22:44.870
I'm not going to bother you
with a long history of this very

00:22:44.870 --> 00:22:45.432
tiny country.

00:22:45.432 --> 00:22:47.390
Although, there are some
historical connections

00:22:47.390 --> 00:22:50.640
between the Netherlands and US.

00:22:50.640 --> 00:22:52.910
There are many
misunderstandings out there.

00:22:52.910 --> 00:22:55.820
Very briefly, some
scholars think

00:22:55.820 --> 00:22:58.280
that the Dutch have pursued
multicultural policies.

00:22:58.280 --> 00:23:00.140
That's not true at all.

00:23:00.140 --> 00:23:02.240
What it's important
to realize is

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:04.660
that we indeed
have some laws that

00:23:04.660 --> 00:23:06.860
stand for more than 100 years.

00:23:10.140 --> 00:23:12.860
They're never very
divided religiously.

00:23:12.860 --> 00:23:18.140
And how to live together
in a harmonious way

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:20.000
while being so different.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:23.930
And therefore, we had a societal
system called pillarization.

00:23:23.930 --> 00:23:26.020
And everybody was locked
up in his own pillar.

00:23:26.020 --> 00:23:27.969
So Protestant pillar,
Roman Catholic pillar--

00:23:27.969 --> 00:23:29.760
and everybody had to
live in those pillars.

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:32.450
And there were no connections,
no right to marry somebody

00:23:32.450 --> 00:23:34.550
from the other pillar.

00:23:34.550 --> 00:23:37.520
And for a long time, that
worked, really, very well.

00:23:37.520 --> 00:23:39.920
But you have to understand
that this pillarization was

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:43.010
experienced over time,
more and more suffocating.

00:23:43.010 --> 00:23:45.260
You were locked up
in your own pillar.

00:23:45.260 --> 00:23:47.734
And you could not even
communicate with others.

00:23:47.734 --> 00:23:49.150
And what's important
to understand

00:23:49.150 --> 00:23:51.830
is that the 1960s
were celebrated

00:23:51.830 --> 00:23:54.650
in this very conservative,
pillarized country--

00:23:54.650 --> 00:23:57.710
the Netherlands-- as an enormous
liberation because people

00:23:57.710 --> 00:24:00.650
could break out of their
pillars and come into contact

00:24:00.650 --> 00:24:03.410
with those of other pillars.

00:24:03.410 --> 00:24:04.850
And there are very
few countries--

00:24:04.850 --> 00:24:06.349
Michele Lamont told
me, perhaps it's

00:24:06.349 --> 00:24:07.610
the same is true for Quebec.

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:10.110
But there are very few
countries, I think,

00:24:10.110 --> 00:24:17.695
that saw such an enormous change
as it did during the late 1960s

00:24:17.695 --> 00:24:19.430
to early 1970s.

00:24:19.430 --> 00:24:23.720
Almost 50% of the
Dutch lost their faith

00:24:23.720 --> 00:24:25.490
in a period of five years.

00:24:25.490 --> 00:24:27.790
Imagine what that
does to the country.

00:24:27.790 --> 00:24:29.210
That's enormous.

00:24:29.210 --> 00:24:32.090
So that became a highly
secularized country,

00:24:32.090 --> 00:24:35.360
celebrating sexual freedom,
and it materialized, also,

00:24:35.360 --> 00:24:37.940
in all kinds of folk as if
laws, as you might know,

00:24:37.940 --> 00:24:41.930
regarding euthanasia,
abortion, drug policies, and--

00:24:41.930 --> 00:24:45.060
somewhat later-- gay marriage,
but the first in the world.

00:24:45.060 --> 00:24:48.020
So May '68 have far
more impact in Amsterdam

00:24:48.020 --> 00:24:51.340
than it had in Paris, to
give a very short summary.

00:24:51.340 --> 00:24:54.440
And and that's interesting,
because the Netherlands,

00:24:54.440 --> 00:24:56.510
being one of the most
conservative countries

00:24:56.510 --> 00:25:00.170
in Europe for a very long
time, became one of the most

00:25:00.170 --> 00:25:02.060
progressive countries.

00:25:02.060 --> 00:25:05.360
And that is now even more
true than in the 1970s because

00:25:05.360 --> 00:25:08.930
over the past decades,
also, populist parties,

00:25:08.930 --> 00:25:11.150
Christian Democrats,
and right wing liberals

00:25:11.150 --> 00:25:15.050
came to share into those liberal
and progressive consensus,

00:25:15.050 --> 00:25:17.720
which is obviously, very
different from the situation

00:25:17.720 --> 00:25:21.170
in the United States, and
in many other countries, UK,

00:25:21.170 --> 00:25:23.690
France, and so on.

00:25:23.690 --> 00:25:26.930
So what happened was that we
were very divided in the 1960s.

00:25:26.930 --> 00:25:29.870
And now we have become
very consensual and not

00:25:29.870 --> 00:25:32.060
hyper diverse.

00:25:32.060 --> 00:25:34.430
And for a while, this
developing consensus

00:25:34.430 --> 00:25:35.880
still respected differences.

00:25:35.880 --> 00:25:38.582
Some differences, some
tolerance was there.

00:25:38.582 --> 00:25:40.040
There was some,
let's say, tolerant

00:25:40.040 --> 00:25:43.610
multiculturalism
towards newcomers, often

00:25:43.610 --> 00:25:46.220
guest workers,
Muslim guest workers,

00:25:46.220 --> 00:25:49.250
but also some tolerance towards
the orthodox Protestants

00:25:49.250 --> 00:25:52.220
who still live in the
Netherlands who are

00:25:52.220 --> 00:25:54.860
a rather small group now today.

00:25:54.860 --> 00:25:57.880
But today, particularly
the Muslim migrants

00:25:57.880 --> 00:26:01.120
are not framed anymore,
are not tolerated anymore,

00:26:01.120 --> 00:26:02.950
they are framed as intolerants.

00:26:02.950 --> 00:26:06.580
And we don't have to be tolerant
towards those who are not

00:26:06.580 --> 00:26:08.270
tolerant towards us, right?

00:26:08.270 --> 00:26:12.800
So this is the intolerance
towards intolerance.

00:26:12.800 --> 00:26:19.400
In this self-image of the
Dutch, in this national story,

00:26:19.400 --> 00:26:23.406
gender and sexuality
play a pivotal role.

00:26:23.406 --> 00:26:24.780
The parliament in
the Netherlands

00:26:24.780 --> 00:26:26.760
doesn't stop talking
about sex and gender.

00:26:26.760 --> 00:26:28.230
It's all the time there.

00:26:28.230 --> 00:26:30.240
Whatever kind of debate
we have, it always

00:26:30.240 --> 00:26:33.642
boils down to topics of
sexuality and gender.

00:26:33.642 --> 00:26:34.350
It's interesting.

00:26:34.350 --> 00:26:35.766
I don't have time
to go into that.

00:26:35.766 --> 00:26:38.370
In some of the Western countries
where we see parallels,

00:26:38.370 --> 00:26:41.880
it's more in the self-image
about gender equality.

00:26:41.880 --> 00:26:43.256
For instance,
Denmark and France.

00:26:43.256 --> 00:26:44.713
In the Netherlands,
it's more about

00:26:44.713 --> 00:26:46.120
sexuality and homosexuality.

00:26:46.120 --> 00:26:49.320
We can think why exactly
those differences are there.

00:26:49.320 --> 00:26:53.430
But it is important to realize
that nowadays, gender equality

00:26:53.430 --> 00:26:58.200
and LGBT rights are considered
as the core of Dutchness,

00:26:58.200 --> 00:27:01.319
also by the far right populist.

00:27:01.319 --> 00:27:03.610
Vilda-- you might have heard
about him-- of the Freedom

00:27:03.610 --> 00:27:06.540
Party, he doesn't stop
talking about how proud he

00:27:06.540 --> 00:27:09.900
is that we have gay
marriage, and also

00:27:09.900 --> 00:27:13.660
the Christian
Democratic Parties.

00:27:13.660 --> 00:27:16.370
We can discuss more about
why the values of the 1960s

00:27:16.370 --> 00:27:18.330
have become so important
in the Netherlands.

00:27:18.330 --> 00:27:20.940
But for sure, in
the past 15 years,

00:27:20.940 --> 00:27:23.780
the embrace of those
values by the populists,

00:27:23.780 --> 00:27:26.920
and by the far right, and
by the liberal right wing,

00:27:26.920 --> 00:27:29.630
American Christian Democrats,
has developed an opposition

00:27:29.630 --> 00:27:30.850
to Muslims.

00:27:30.850 --> 00:27:35.370
That has been the core reasoning
and the logic is very simple.

00:27:35.370 --> 00:27:37.640
The enemy of my
enemy is my friend.

00:27:37.640 --> 00:27:40.370
And then there was
the idea that Muslims

00:27:40.370 --> 00:27:42.950
can never care for
gender equality

00:27:42.950 --> 00:27:46.300
or can never be LGBTI friendly.

00:27:46.300 --> 00:27:51.470
Other scholars, [INAUDIBLE],,
John Scott, [INAUDIBLE],,

00:27:51.470 --> 00:27:53.030
have labeled this
development, as you

00:27:53.030 --> 00:27:57.080
might know, as homo-nationalism
or female nationalism.

00:27:57.080 --> 00:27:58.760
Progressive forms
of nationalism that

00:27:58.760 --> 00:28:01.880
put the women's movement
and the LGBT movement,

00:28:01.880 --> 00:28:05.030
but also queer Muslims and
feminist movements in a very

00:28:05.030 --> 00:28:06.860
difficult position,
because the moment

00:28:06.860 --> 00:28:08.987
you mobilize for
those values, it

00:28:08.987 --> 00:28:10.820
looks as if you are
immediately anti-Muslim,

00:28:10.820 --> 00:28:14.250
and the other way around.

00:28:14.250 --> 00:28:16.260
So the problem is--

00:28:16.260 --> 00:28:18.470
it is fantastic, at
least in my perspective--

00:28:18.470 --> 00:28:21.800
that progressive values
are broadly embraced,

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:23.660
but at whose expense?

00:28:23.660 --> 00:28:25.720
I think we should
think about that.

00:28:30.020 --> 00:28:31.680
And what does it produce?

00:28:31.680 --> 00:28:35.590
It produces a self image
as if the Dutch have always

00:28:35.590 --> 00:28:37.100
been that progressive.

00:28:37.100 --> 00:28:39.620
So now, the story is that
since the 17th century,

00:28:39.620 --> 00:28:44.440
the Dutch always embraced LGBT
rights and women's rights.

00:28:44.440 --> 00:28:46.540
And it is totally essentialized.

00:28:46.540 --> 00:28:49.081
It actually doesn't do much
justice to the history,

00:28:49.081 --> 00:28:50.455
as I already
explained to you, we

00:28:50.455 --> 00:28:52.246
were one of the most
conservative countries

00:28:52.246 --> 00:28:53.930
in Europe.

00:28:53.930 --> 00:28:57.700
And Muslims then are also
fixed in their identities.

00:28:57.700 --> 00:28:59.680
They're eternally backwards.

00:28:59.680 --> 00:29:02.890
They are unchangeable
and unchanging.

00:29:02.890 --> 00:29:04.870
It means the rise of nativism.

00:29:04.870 --> 00:29:06.670
It means that some
people are considered

00:29:06.670 --> 00:29:09.340
to be more truly Dutch
because they embrace

00:29:09.340 --> 00:29:12.340
LGBT rights and women's rights.

00:29:12.340 --> 00:29:14.620
And those are then
the white Dutch.

00:29:14.620 --> 00:29:17.590
They consider themselves
as being the true Dutch

00:29:17.590 --> 00:29:20.086
because they are so progressive.

00:29:23.460 --> 00:29:24.960
And that brings me
to my last slide.

00:29:24.960 --> 00:29:27.510
So I'm quite fine
on time, I guess.

00:29:27.510 --> 00:29:30.180
And it's somewhat linking
to the second panel

00:29:30.180 --> 00:29:33.240
we had this morning.

00:29:33.240 --> 00:29:35.040
Why would it be an
important story?

00:29:35.040 --> 00:29:38.270
I almost apologetically said,
we shouldn't talk too much

00:29:38.270 --> 00:29:39.020
about Netherlands.

00:29:39.020 --> 00:29:41.620
But it's not just
about the Netherlands.

00:29:41.620 --> 00:29:43.310
There is a broader story here.

00:29:43.310 --> 00:29:46.250
And let me draw
four conclusions,

00:29:46.250 --> 00:29:49.740
give four reasons why this
is an important story.

00:29:49.740 --> 00:29:52.620
First of all, it's part
of a broader tendency

00:29:52.620 --> 00:29:55.770
in which the most progressive
countries in Europe

00:29:55.770 --> 00:29:58.740
become the most
migrant unfriendly.

00:29:58.740 --> 00:30:03.550
You might have heard how harsh
the Danish people, Denmark,

00:30:03.550 --> 00:30:05.400
for example, has become.

00:30:05.400 --> 00:30:07.620
Another country, like
all the Nordic countries

00:30:07.620 --> 00:30:10.290
that are always
outstandingly progressive,

00:30:10.290 --> 00:30:13.950
have become very harsh and
don't want to accept migrants

00:30:13.950 --> 00:30:16.880
so easily anymore.

00:30:16.880 --> 00:30:19.620
Second, why is it
an important story?

00:30:19.620 --> 00:30:21.560
Because among the
Populist Party,

00:30:21.560 --> 00:30:25.650
things are happening that you
might, perhaps, not expect.

00:30:25.650 --> 00:30:30.570
Even though Trump also
sometimes mentions LGBTI rights

00:30:30.570 --> 00:30:32.100
and women's rights--

00:30:32.100 --> 00:30:34.530
obviously, for highly
opportunistic reasons--

00:30:34.530 --> 00:30:37.890
but we have to understand
why populist parties are

00:30:37.890 --> 00:30:40.070
embracing that discourse.

00:30:40.070 --> 00:30:41.070
And we see it happening.

00:30:41.070 --> 00:30:42.160
It started in Denmark.

00:30:42.160 --> 00:30:44.310
Then the Netherlands,
Germany, France.

00:30:44.310 --> 00:30:47.730
So almost all Western European
countries, these very strong

00:30:47.730 --> 00:30:51.780
populist parties, are more in
this discourse in which they

00:30:51.780 --> 00:30:54.210
claim modernity,
in which they claim

00:30:54.210 --> 00:30:58.470
