ethnic nationalism in Turkey,

00:39:00.650 --> 00:39:02.510
that ought to be something.

00:39:02.510 --> 00:39:07.400
But I lost that's when I started
working on the Armenian issue.

00:39:07.400 --> 00:39:10.010
And I looked and
wrote a book on why

00:39:10.010 --> 00:39:12.620
the Armenian Genocide and
the collective violence

00:39:12.620 --> 00:39:17.180
against the Armenians has
been denied by Turkish state

00:39:17.180 --> 00:39:20.300
and society for 220 years.

00:39:20.300 --> 00:39:23.930
As a consequence of which,
everybody was sure that I was

00:39:23.930 --> 00:39:28.580
of Armenian origin because they
cannot imagine that I could be

00:39:28.580 --> 00:39:34.070
an ethnic Turk, which tells
you about this ontological

00:39:34.070 --> 00:39:36.920
nationalism that
I'm talking about.

00:39:36.920 --> 00:39:40.110
And then of course, I came here.

00:39:40.110 --> 00:39:44.180
And when I was
here, as I said, I

00:39:44.180 --> 00:39:47.300
live here, I have had a
lot of experience here,

00:39:47.300 --> 00:39:49.220
I have actually lived
here more than I

00:39:49.220 --> 00:39:53.870
have in Turkey at this
point, but I am still seen

00:39:53.870 --> 00:39:55.790
as Turkish to a certain degree.

00:39:55.790 --> 00:39:57.770
And this, I think,
is what we ought

00:39:57.770 --> 00:40:03.710
to think about when we
think about, what is it?

00:40:03.710 --> 00:40:06.920
We have to look at the
assumptions of whiteness,

00:40:06.920 --> 00:40:12.440
not only in terms of exclusion,
but in terms of inclusion,

00:40:12.440 --> 00:40:14.510
or resisting that inclusion.

00:40:14.510 --> 00:40:19.800
Because obviously, I speak
English with an accent.

00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:21.830
So I would they would
say to me, oh, you know,

00:40:21.830 --> 00:40:24.200
wonderful, I'm
great, and all that.

00:40:24.200 --> 00:40:26.880
And they say,
where are you from?

00:40:26.880 --> 00:40:28.550
I'm now in Ann Arbor.

00:40:28.550 --> 00:40:31.650
I would say New Jersey because
I came to Princeton, right?

00:40:31.650 --> 00:40:35.540
I mean, but it's a test.

00:40:35.540 --> 00:40:40.220
So then they would say,
where are you really from?

00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:44.070
So I would say yes
because I'm not going to--

00:40:44.070 --> 00:40:47.840
I mean, I refuse to have
them pigeon hole me.

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:52.310
It's actually very
interesting about the person,

00:40:52.310 --> 00:40:56.690
the author who was talking,
she refused to be pigeonholed.

00:40:56.690 --> 00:40:58.610
But I think that's
something that

00:40:58.610 --> 00:41:04.550
comes from those of us who have
lived in more than one context.

00:41:04.550 --> 00:41:08.420
That is, I think, the vision
of the future that will get us

00:41:08.420 --> 00:41:10.400
beyond multiculturalism.

00:41:10.400 --> 00:41:15.350
But in order to get, basically,
insight into how that would

00:41:15.350 --> 00:41:17.840
work, I don't only
look at Turkey,

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:20.540
I also look at
the United States.

00:41:20.540 --> 00:41:25.460
Who do you think inspires me in
the United States, you may ask.

00:41:25.460 --> 00:41:33.020
I would say WEB Dubois is my
amazing hero at the moment

00:41:33.020 --> 00:41:38.230
because only he
captures what I feel

00:41:38.230 --> 00:41:41.140
through his notion of
double consciousness.

00:41:41.140 --> 00:41:45.850
I mean, of course,
I will never presume

00:41:45.850 --> 00:41:49.450
to have the violent past
that African-Americans

00:41:49.450 --> 00:41:51.020
have had in this country.

00:41:51.020 --> 00:41:52.690
That's not what I meant.

00:41:52.690 --> 00:41:56.770
But I mean in terms of
belonging and not belonging.

00:41:56.770 --> 00:42:00.430
And that, of course, makes
me think at the same time

00:42:00.430 --> 00:42:05.890
that, how is it that we can
go beyond this ontological

00:42:05.890 --> 00:42:08.650
nationalism that
leaves people out,

00:42:08.650 --> 00:42:12.160
that doesn't leave
spaces for people?

00:42:12.160 --> 00:42:15.670
I mean, that is the
polarization that's leading us.

00:42:15.670 --> 00:42:20.560
At least the other view, they
enabled you to still continue

00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:22.600
living in that society.

00:42:22.600 --> 00:42:25.660
When you have
ontological nationalism,

00:42:25.660 --> 00:42:29.090
they want you to disappear.

00:42:29.090 --> 00:42:30.850
They want to send you back.

00:42:30.850 --> 00:42:34.360
They don't allow that
space for you even here.

00:42:34.360 --> 00:42:36.040
Where does that come from?

00:42:36.040 --> 00:42:41.410
I mean, I will talk in more
detail about what is in Turkey.

00:42:41.410 --> 00:42:44.740
But because I have
lived in both societies,

00:42:44.740 --> 00:42:49.090
I always ask the same
questions of both societies

00:42:49.090 --> 00:42:51.280
because I don't think
it is fair for me

00:42:51.280 --> 00:42:54.790
to be only critical
in one or the other.

00:42:54.790 --> 00:42:57.910
I have to be able to ask
the same questions in both.

00:43:02.010 --> 00:43:04.390
And of course, I
am very informed,

00:43:04.390 --> 00:43:08.350
let's say, by critical race
theory and feminist theory.

00:43:08.350 --> 00:43:13.390
As a consequence, the insights
I have in analyzing and teaching

00:43:13.390 --> 00:43:17.230
my students here-- most of
whom, of course, are Americans--

00:43:17.230 --> 00:43:22.030
belong to and necessitate that
I know about American history.

00:43:22.030 --> 00:43:25.150
But by specialization
on the Middle East,

00:43:25.150 --> 00:43:27.490
also, it necessitates
that I know there.

00:43:27.490 --> 00:43:29.710
And of course, my
own experiences

00:43:29.710 --> 00:43:31.740
in the first half
of my life enabled

00:43:31.740 --> 00:43:33.940
me to also know that context.

00:43:33.940 --> 00:43:37.090
If you look into
the United States,

00:43:37.090 --> 00:43:43.780
I think we have to have a
total reinterpretation of what

00:43:43.780 --> 00:43:46.960
it is to belong into
the United States.

00:43:46.960 --> 00:43:50.560
And I would do that
on two grounds.

00:43:50.560 --> 00:43:53.980
One is, of course, the
grounds of intersectionality,

00:43:53.980 --> 00:44:01.460
that first was developed
by Patricia Hill Collins'

00:44:01.460 --> 00:44:02.760
matrix of domination.

00:44:02.760 --> 00:44:06.780
And then, developed by King
Berkeley [INAUDIBLE] notion

00:44:06.780 --> 00:44:11.460
of, you get public visibility,
in that case, for black women,

00:44:11.460 --> 00:44:14.310
because they are excluded
from the civil rights

00:44:14.310 --> 00:44:16.850
movement for being
women and from the

00:44:16.850 --> 00:44:22.710
for the feminist
movement for being black.

00:44:22.710 --> 00:44:28.320
I mean, the argument there
is you have to look at it

00:44:28.320 --> 00:44:31.470
not only one category
in a society,

00:44:31.470 --> 00:44:33.570
you have to look
at the intersection

00:44:33.570 --> 00:44:36.960
of multiple categories
to see the inequality

00:44:36.960 --> 00:44:39.570
in power relations
that are hidden there.

00:44:39.570 --> 00:44:41.740
So that is one insight.

00:44:41.740 --> 00:44:46.740
And if you do that, I think, as
we saw with the working class,

00:44:46.740 --> 00:44:49.710
you see the variation.

00:44:49.710 --> 00:44:52.500
I like the fact that you
said white working class,

00:44:52.500 --> 00:44:55.740
because I think that has
very different dynamics

00:44:55.740 --> 00:45:01.020
than the non-white working class
and the issues faced by them.

00:45:03.700 --> 00:45:04.980
So that is the intersection.

00:45:04.980 --> 00:45:09.030
And the second
thing, I think, is

00:45:09.030 --> 00:45:14.910
history and the foundational
violences in our society

00:45:14.910 --> 00:45:17.820
that haven't been
adequately addressed.

00:45:17.820 --> 00:45:25.200
In our context in the United
States, if you think about--

00:45:25.200 --> 00:45:29.070
and I will do this in Turkey,
but I'm starting by doing it

00:45:29.070 --> 00:45:30.750
in the United States--

00:45:30.750 --> 00:45:36.510
what are the foundational social
actors of the United States?

00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:40.230
Who have made the
United States possible?

00:45:40.230 --> 00:45:42.360
Our foundation
within this country

00:45:42.360 --> 00:45:45.420
is settled on white settlers.

00:45:45.420 --> 00:45:48.700
Yes, we say, we the
people, but who are we?

00:45:48.700 --> 00:45:51.730
And who is included in
the we and who isn't?

00:45:51.730 --> 00:45:54.710
I would argue that there
are three social actors.

00:45:54.710 --> 00:45:56.670
That are the white settlers.

00:45:56.670 --> 00:45:59.460
There are the Native
Americans whose lands

00:45:59.460 --> 00:46:01.290
we have built everything on.

00:46:01.290 --> 00:46:03.000
And there are the
African-Americans

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:06.250
who provided the labor
for all that to happen.

00:46:06.250 --> 00:46:08.550
Look at our
ontological nationalism

00:46:08.550 --> 00:46:10.110
in the United States.

00:46:10.110 --> 00:46:13.500
We only acknowledge one group.

00:46:13.500 --> 00:46:15.210
We do not acknowledge the other.

00:46:15.210 --> 00:46:17.700
Not only do we not
acknowledge it,

00:46:17.700 --> 00:46:19.380
they are the ones
who are suffering

00:46:19.380 --> 00:46:21.960
the most in the United States.

00:46:21.960 --> 00:46:24.140
And I'm not talking about
the other non-whites who

00:46:24.140 --> 00:46:26.400
have come later
in various forms,

00:46:26.400 --> 00:46:29.040
I'm just saying foundational.

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:33.060
So that is the framework I want
you to think about when I now

00:46:33.060 --> 00:46:35.820
turn to Turkey and
explain to you what

00:46:35.820 --> 00:46:39.000
happens in that context
because that's obviously

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:40.890
what I specialize in.

00:46:40.890 --> 00:46:43.950
If you look at Turkey and
the nationalism in Turkey,

00:46:43.950 --> 00:46:47.430
we do have Tayyip
Erdogan, the president,

00:46:47.430 --> 00:46:50.130
and we do have, of
course, Trump here.

00:46:50.130 --> 00:46:53.670
In my life, the two
people intersect

00:46:53.670 --> 00:46:55.410
in a very interesting way.

00:46:55.410 --> 00:47:01.170
Because of the work I have
done in Turkey with respect

00:47:01.170 --> 00:47:04.410
to the Armenian Genocide
followed by the fact that I are

00:47:04.410 --> 00:47:08.880
now working on the Kurds
because I focus on minorities,

00:47:08.880 --> 00:47:12.900
and as a consequence, the
state violence, and others,

00:47:12.900 --> 00:47:17.220
and I signed a petition-- along
with [INAUDIBLE] who is was

00:47:17.220 --> 00:47:23.340
my friend in crime,
a fellow terrorist--

00:47:23.340 --> 00:47:25.410
saying Kurds should
not be killed,

00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:30.660
you should talk to them
instead, the president Erdogan,

00:47:30.660 --> 00:47:32.830
said that we were terrorists.

00:47:32.830 --> 00:47:37.170
He said there is no difference
between a terrorist machine

00:47:37.170 --> 00:47:40.200
gun and a scholar's pen.

00:47:40.200 --> 00:47:45.540
So as a consequence, since then,
I cannot go back to Turkey.

00:47:45.540 --> 00:47:46.760
So I have--

00:47:46.760 --> 00:47:50.160
I mean, I have
Turkish citizenship,

00:47:50.160 --> 00:47:51.720
but who knows for how long.

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:54.570
I mean, I haven't been able
to go back for three years.

00:47:54.570 --> 00:47:58.500
So recently, after Trump's
election, my mother,

00:47:58.500 --> 00:48:01.140
who is back in Turkey,
occasionally keeps

00:48:01.140 --> 00:48:04.740
calling whenever I go
on international talks,

00:48:04.740 --> 00:48:06.660
and she says, have
you gotten back?

00:48:06.660 --> 00:48:07.490
Is it OK?

00:48:07.490 --> 00:48:10.710
And I'm saying, yeah,
I'm an American citizen.

00:48:10.710 --> 00:48:12.020
What do you think?

00:48:12.020 --> 00:48:14.610
Then the truth came out.

00:48:14.610 --> 00:48:17.460
She said, look, you
had two citizenships.

00:48:17.460 --> 00:48:20.250
You basically now
cannot go to Turkey.

00:48:20.250 --> 00:48:21.660
You're down to one.

00:48:21.660 --> 00:48:27.090
So don't make too much
noise because you'll

00:48:27.090 --> 00:48:28.920
have no other place to go.

00:48:28.920 --> 00:48:31.020
I said, mom, don't you worry.

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:35.730
I'm very close to
Windsor, Canada.

00:48:35.730 --> 00:48:37.770
I could always go there.

00:48:37.770 --> 00:48:39.840
I mean, so that is the other--

00:48:39.840 --> 00:48:42.810
with respect to
nationalisms in Turkey,

00:48:42.810 --> 00:48:47.040
what we have today, I think,
is a much more violent form

00:48:47.040 --> 00:48:50.640
of ontological
destruction in a way

00:48:50.640 --> 00:48:55.170
because there were initially
four founding social actors

00:48:55.170 --> 00:48:59.720
in the transition from Empire
to nation state in that context.

00:48:59.720 --> 00:49:04.170
There were the Greeks who
were then basically scared

00:49:04.170 --> 00:49:09.050
and about 300,000 were
forced to migrate, also

00:49:09.050 --> 00:49:11.690
through population
exchange, to Greece.

00:49:11.690 --> 00:49:14.930
There were the Armenians
who also claimed,

00:49:14.930 --> 00:49:17.990
of course-- these are the
four social actors that

00:49:17.990 --> 00:49:22.760
claimed Turkey as
their ancestral lands.

00:49:22.760 --> 00:49:25.310
Greeks were sent to Greece.

00:49:25.310 --> 00:49:28.310
Armenians were, of
course, destroyed

00:49:28.310 --> 00:49:30.410
through the Armenian Genocide.

00:49:30.410 --> 00:49:34.390
That left the Kurds and the
Turks together initially.

00:49:34.390 --> 00:49:37.100
What happened was that,
when you look at history

00:49:37.100 --> 00:49:39.950
and what happened
in the transition

00:49:39.950 --> 00:49:45.500
in writing our foundation myth
until the republic was founded,

00:49:45.500 --> 00:49:50.540
the Kurds were seen as one
of the two essential actors

00:49:50.540 --> 00:49:52.790
of the Turkish Republic.

00:49:52.790 --> 00:49:56.450
Once the borders
were put in place,

00:49:56.450 --> 00:50:01.460
all mention of Kurdish
element is totally silenced.

00:50:01.460 --> 00:50:05.360
And I think that
explains very well why

00:50:05.360 --> 00:50:11.390
we have the violence and
the approval of violence

00:50:11.390 --> 00:50:16.040
not only by Turkish state,
also by Turkish society

00:50:16.040 --> 00:50:17.900
as we see in Afrin.

00:50:17.900 --> 00:50:20.780
Because in Afrin,
not only have Turks,

00:50:20.780 --> 00:50:22.790
the Turkish military
had gone in there

00:50:22.790 --> 00:50:29.180
and destroyed, and massacred,
and plundered all Kurdish

00:50:29.180 --> 00:50:30.890
people and property.

00:50:30.890 --> 00:50:36.020
But they say they did it,
of course, with all the arms

00:50:36.020 --> 00:50:39.410
and armaments that the United
States and Europe provided

00:50:39.410 --> 00:50:40.610
for Turkey.

00:50:40.610 --> 00:50:44.690
And we haven't done anything
about it in the United States.

00:50:44.690 --> 00:50:48.920
So for me, therefore, you cannot
separate what goes on in Turkey

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:52.640
and the nationalism there
from what we are doing here

00:50:52.640 --> 00:50:58.240
because if you separate it, what
disappears is responsibility.

00:50:58.240 --> 00:51:00.250
And we have to, I
think, bring back

00:51:00.250 --> 00:51:02.290
that more moral responsibility.

00:51:02.290 --> 00:51:04.450
And I'll leave there
