00:53:05.470 --> 00:53:08.590
this is not the America I know.

00:53:08.590 --> 00:53:12.610
And I wanted to start my
brief remarks with this phrase

00:53:12.610 --> 00:53:15.280
because I feel like I've heard
it so much in the last year,

00:53:15.280 --> 00:53:18.160
or really the last
several years.

00:53:18.160 --> 00:53:22.750
And I feel like it captures
a great deal of the--

00:53:22.750 --> 00:53:24.510
I have turmoil in my notes.

00:53:24.510 --> 00:53:28.390
And I think that's maybe
not an inaccurate word,

00:53:28.390 --> 00:53:31.540
but the turmoil that we've
been trying to consider

00:53:31.540 --> 00:53:32.570
during this conference.

00:53:32.570 --> 00:53:35.560
So this phrase is
fundamentally about questions

00:53:35.560 --> 00:53:39.610
of citizenship and belonging,
but also ownership.

00:53:39.610 --> 00:53:40.570
Who owns America?

00:53:40.570 --> 00:53:43.129
Who gets to decide
what America is?

00:53:43.129 --> 00:53:45.670
So notice that for me, there
are two questions embedded here,

00:53:45.670 --> 00:53:48.310
not just who belongs
to the nation,

00:53:48.310 --> 00:53:51.460
but who does the
nation belong to.

00:53:51.460 --> 00:53:54.130
I think both of those are
equally important questions.

00:53:54.130 --> 00:53:56.620
And so I've heard this
phrase, or some version of it,

00:53:56.620 --> 00:54:00.610
from multiple places across the
political spectrum, certainly

00:54:00.610 --> 00:54:03.970
with the election
results last year.

00:54:03.970 --> 00:54:06.010
I've heard this phrase
for many progressives,

00:54:06.010 --> 00:54:09.730
many of my colleagues,
students, those

00:54:09.730 --> 00:54:14.980
who mean to disavow what
they read, the Trump election

00:54:14.980 --> 00:54:17.230
victory and presidency
to represent.

00:54:17.230 --> 00:54:18.910
I initially started
with the goal of,

00:54:18.910 --> 00:54:21.580
I'm not going to
say Trump, but I

00:54:21.580 --> 00:54:26.130
think that's both
silly and inaccurate.

00:54:26.130 --> 00:54:27.310
So I put it right in there.

00:54:27.310 --> 00:54:29.330
I've heard this phrase
from immigrants,

00:54:29.330 --> 00:54:32.650
people like my
parents who came here

00:54:32.650 --> 00:54:34.990
50 years ago to
complete their education

00:54:34.990 --> 00:54:39.790
and build a better life for
themselves and their kids

00:54:39.790 --> 00:54:44.080
and to send their daughter to
Harvard to get a PhD, a better

00:54:44.080 --> 00:54:46.330
life than the one that
they thought they could

00:54:46.330 --> 00:54:49.570
have in their native homes.

00:54:49.570 --> 00:54:51.340
But I've also heard
it in different forms

00:54:51.340 --> 00:54:53.710
before Trump's
election from those

00:54:53.710 --> 00:54:55.960
who opposed Obama in
his presidency, who

00:54:55.960 --> 00:54:59.950
opposed Hillary's candidacy,
and the Democrats in general

00:54:59.950 --> 00:55:02.350
in certain ways.

00:55:02.350 --> 00:55:06.250
And then lastly, I have
to add that I have not

00:55:06.250 --> 00:55:10.090
heard this phrase from too many
of my African-American friends,

00:55:10.090 --> 00:55:13.360
and colleagues, and family
who have been much more

00:55:13.360 --> 00:55:16.109
likely to say,
often with a smirk,

00:55:16.109 --> 00:55:18.400
I don't know, but it seems
pretty much like the America

00:55:18.400 --> 00:55:20.500
we've always known.

00:55:20.500 --> 00:55:23.550
So there's something there that
we also need to think about.

00:55:23.550 --> 00:55:24.050
All right.

00:55:24.050 --> 00:55:28.330
So we all know how tribal
American politics has become.

00:55:28.330 --> 00:55:31.030
There's no need to recap
that in any amount of detail.

00:55:31.030 --> 00:55:32.630
So I'm not going to do that.

00:55:32.630 --> 00:55:35.320
What is striking to me though,
as a scholar of nationalism,

00:55:35.320 --> 00:55:39.570
is that this partisan
tribalism is actually

00:55:39.570 --> 00:55:41.700
about the very
nature and definition

00:55:41.700 --> 00:55:43.950
of the nation itself.

00:55:43.950 --> 00:55:46.830
It's about what
America actually is.

00:55:46.830 --> 00:55:51.210
It's not about what's good or
bad for America, or the best

00:55:51.210 --> 00:55:54.840
paths forward for America, or
even how to correct past policy

00:55:54.840 --> 00:55:56.670
mistakes or anything like that.

00:55:56.670 --> 00:56:00.690
Anything that normal political
processes can, at some level,

00:56:00.690 --> 00:56:01.830
handle.

00:56:01.830 --> 00:56:04.080
Instead, what's up for
debate is the very core

00:56:04.080 --> 00:56:07.200
question of what America is.

00:56:07.200 --> 00:56:11.470
Just a quick disclaimer, I
want to throw in at this point.

00:56:11.470 --> 00:56:14.080
In this talk, I will use
America to mean the US.

00:56:14.080 --> 00:56:18.310
But I also want to acknowledge,
and I understand that doing so

00:56:18.310 --> 00:56:20.680
can serve to alight
all the other countries

00:56:20.680 --> 00:56:24.860
of the hemisphere, though
that is not my intention.

00:56:24.860 --> 00:56:29.930
It's a simplifying
tool for me right now.

00:56:29.930 --> 00:56:32.630
So I study Indian politics.

00:56:32.630 --> 00:56:35.360
And within that, I focus
on all those things

00:56:35.360 --> 00:56:38.160
that David mentioned,
religion, gender nationalism,

00:56:38.160 --> 00:56:41.720
I really do try to look at
how they all mush together,

00:56:41.720 --> 00:56:45.260
as well as law, and democracy,
and political parties.

00:56:45.260 --> 00:56:47.150
You can't really study
one without the other.

00:56:50.210 --> 00:56:51.890
And in some ways,
it's weird not to be

00:56:51.890 --> 00:56:53.360
talking about India today.

00:56:53.360 --> 00:56:55.250
I'm actually focusing
on the US, which

00:56:55.250 --> 00:56:58.220
is in certain ways kind of
freeing in some of the ways

00:56:58.220 --> 00:57:02.370
that Jhumpa Lahiri talked about.

00:57:02.370 --> 00:57:05.540
And what I want to
say is that when

00:57:05.540 --> 00:57:07.734
I see what's going
on in US politics--

00:57:07.734 --> 00:57:09.650
I mean, in the sense
that Fatima talked about,

00:57:09.650 --> 00:57:13.181
you can't study Indian
politics, but I've been educated

00:57:13.181 --> 00:57:14.930
and growing my whole
life in this country,

00:57:14.930 --> 00:57:16.888
and you can't get a degree
in political science

00:57:16.888 --> 00:57:20.330
without knowing about American
politics in an academic sense

00:57:20.330 --> 00:57:22.310
as well as in a personal sense.

00:57:22.310 --> 00:57:25.280
So I feel entirely comfortable
talking about US politics.

00:57:25.280 --> 00:57:28.970
But when I see what's going
on, I sort of naturally

00:57:28.970 --> 00:57:33.170
try to draw on what I know
about nationalism in general

00:57:33.170 --> 00:57:34.299
to try to make sense of it.

00:57:34.299 --> 00:57:35.840
So that's a little
bit of what I want

00:57:35.840 --> 00:57:38.810
to try to share with you today.

00:57:38.810 --> 00:57:40.940
And in fact, for someone
who studied nationalism

00:57:40.940 --> 00:57:45.450
in many forms all over
the world for a few years,

00:57:45.450 --> 00:57:48.710
if not decades, it
actually seems crystal

00:57:48.710 --> 00:57:50.260
clear to me what's going on.

00:57:50.260 --> 00:57:52.880
Or at least I feel
like I can make

00:57:52.880 --> 00:57:54.500
some sense of our
current situation

00:57:54.500 --> 00:57:57.301
in terms that I know from
studying nationalism.

00:57:57.301 --> 00:57:59.550
And again, that's what I
want to share with you today.

00:57:59.550 --> 00:58:02.390
So for many decades,
scholars of nationalism

00:58:02.390 --> 00:58:06.200
have drawn a distinction
between two different types

00:58:06.200 --> 00:58:09.320
or forms of nationalism that
I have listed here for you.

00:58:09.320 --> 00:58:12.260
They've gone by different
names at different times.

00:58:12.260 --> 00:58:14.270
But at root, I
think they can best

00:58:14.270 --> 00:58:17.660
be described and understood as
ethnic and civic nationalism.

00:58:17.660 --> 00:58:20.630
Ethnic nationalism represents
a community of descent,

00:58:20.630 --> 00:58:23.810
D-E-S-C-E-N-T, not
descent into chaos,

00:58:23.810 --> 00:58:25.910
but like bloodline descent--

00:58:25.910 --> 00:58:29.240
maybe descent into
chaos, too, eventually.

00:58:29.240 --> 00:58:34.710
The ethnic nation is rooted
in sociocultural loyalties.

00:58:34.710 --> 00:58:36.650
The nation's
constituted on the basis

00:58:36.650 --> 00:58:39.680
of bloodlines, whether
real, or imagined,

00:58:39.680 --> 00:58:42.350
or believed, kin-like relations.

00:58:42.350 --> 00:58:46.790
So an ethnic nation is like one
big family, whether it's happy

00:58:46.790 --> 00:58:47.540
or not.

00:58:47.540 --> 00:58:50.040
Civic nationalism,
on the other hand,

00:58:50.040 --> 00:58:52.100
is based in political
institutional ties.

00:58:52.100 --> 00:58:56.630
It's more about shared political
beliefs, shared ideology

00:58:56.630 --> 00:58:59.510
rather than a shared
ethnic background.

00:58:59.510 --> 00:59:01.490
Now, notice that in
ethnic nationalism,

00:59:01.490 --> 00:59:03.140
you're born into a nation.

00:59:03.140 --> 00:59:07.640
You can't choose, or change,
or abandon your nationality.

00:59:07.640 --> 00:59:09.710
Whereas, in civic
nationalism, citizenship

00:59:09.710 --> 00:59:10.760
is a matter of choice.

00:59:10.760 --> 00:59:12.560
You can choose to
leave one nationality.

00:59:12.560 --> 00:59:15.140
You can pledge
loyalty to another one

00:59:15.140 --> 00:59:17.037
as long as you are
pledging loyalty

00:59:17.037 --> 00:59:18.120
to the beliefs and ideas--

00:59:18.120 --> 00:59:18.980
[AUDIENCE SNEEZE]

00:59:18.980 --> 00:59:20.780
--that constitute that nation.

00:59:20.780 --> 00:59:23.960
Bless you.

00:59:23.960 --> 00:59:26.387
And obviously, then,
both the question--

00:59:26.387 --> 00:59:28.970
I hope that doesn't mean you are
allergic to the framework I'm

00:59:28.970 --> 00:59:31.260
putting up.

00:59:31.260 --> 00:59:34.550
I will go into that
Q&amp;A. So obviously

00:59:34.550 --> 00:59:37.010
then, both the question of
who belongs to the nation

00:59:37.010 --> 00:59:39.860
and who the nation belongs
to, both those questions

00:59:39.860 --> 00:59:43.640
are answered very differently
in civic and ethnic nationalism.

00:59:43.640 --> 00:59:48.739
Ethnic nationalism, you
either belong to the group,

00:59:48.739 --> 00:59:49.280
or you don't.

00:59:49.280 --> 00:59:51.770
You were born into
it, or you weren't.

00:59:51.770 --> 00:59:54.530
Whereas, civic nationalism,
anyone, in theory,

00:59:54.530 --> 00:59:57.647
could belong to the nation.

00:59:57.647 --> 00:59:59.480
And so hopefully, at
this point, many of you

00:59:59.480 --> 01:00:01.479
can figure out where I'm
trying to go with this.

01:00:01.479 --> 01:00:03.001
I believe that the
US is struggling

01:00:03.001 --> 01:00:05.000
with the question of
whether we're fundamentally

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:06.980
a civic or an ethnic nation.

01:00:06.980 --> 01:00:09.320
And to be explicit,
America has long

01:00:09.320 --> 01:00:13.070
gotten by with the veneer
or, more cynically, the myth

01:00:13.070 --> 01:00:15.050
of being a civic nation.

01:00:15.050 --> 01:00:19.520
And I think that we could get
away with that for so long

01:00:19.520 --> 01:00:23.240
as the underpinning ethnic
basis of our civic nationalism

01:00:23.240 --> 01:00:26.870
remained dominant,
even if dormant.

01:00:26.870 --> 01:00:32.000
And we all know what that ethnic
basis is, it's Judeo-Christian.

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:35.300
Perhaps even more accurately,
Anglo-Saxon Protestant,

01:00:35.300 --> 01:00:38.570
primarily of European
descent, and white,

01:00:38.570 --> 01:00:41.600
however that's defined at
any given historical moment.

01:00:41.600 --> 01:00:46.220
But now, we're reaching a
tipping point as the US becomes

01:00:46.220 --> 01:00:47.900
a minority-majority nation--

01:00:47.900 --> 01:00:50.960
or maybe it's majority-minority,
I am never clear--

01:00:50.960 --> 01:00:54.590
that ethnic foundation
is threatened.

01:00:54.590 --> 01:00:58.370
Certain groups of people feel
or sense that that foundation

01:00:58.370 --> 01:00:59.580
is threatened.

01:00:59.580 --> 01:01:02.520
And so that foundation is
trying to reassert itself.

01:01:02.520 --> 01:01:06.080
Or those people are trying to
reassert it, the people who

01:01:06.080 --> 01:01:09.680
feel the sense of threat.

01:01:09.680 --> 01:01:12.260
And these groups, these
elements, I believe,

01:01:12.260 --> 01:01:14.090
are the ones that not
only openly support

01:01:14.090 --> 01:01:17.120
Trump, that 30%
of the population

01:01:17.120 --> 01:01:19.170
that will never budge
from supporting him.

01:01:19.170 --> 01:01:21.560
But also, I think very
significant numbers

01:01:21.560 --> 01:01:26.120
of people, that
middle 30% to 40%,

01:01:26.120 --> 01:01:29.880
who feel the vague and easiness
of not really liking Trump,

01:01:29.880 --> 01:01:33.110
they don't like Trump,
to some extent, I think,

01:01:33.110 --> 01:01:36.020
maybe what Joan called
the sensible voters,

01:01:36.020 --> 01:01:38.510
but they don't really
like the other side.

01:01:38.510 --> 01:01:41.000
They don't trust where they
think the country is headed

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:42.680
or where the other
side is either

01:01:42.680 --> 01:01:48.200
trying to take the country,
or seems willing to let it go.

01:01:48.200 --> 01:01:52.610
A couple of things to
note regarding the debate

01:01:52.610 --> 01:01:54.200
framed in this way.

01:01:54.200 --> 01:01:57.620
First, the US has not
just been considered

01:01:57.620 --> 01:02:00.620
and considers itself to be
a civic nation, but really,

01:02:00.620 --> 01:02:02.730
the ultimate example
of a civic nation.

01:02:02.730 --> 01:02:07.760
We're supposed to be the example
to show that civic nationalism

01:02:07.760 --> 01:02:09.371
really worked.

01:02:09.371 --> 01:02:11.120
What we all share that
makes us Americans,

01:02:11.120 --> 01:02:13.040
a set of beliefs,
an ideology, we

01:02:13.040 --> 01:02:17.880
believe in democracy, individual
freedoms, et cetera, et cetera.

01:02:17.880 --> 01:02:20.120
And then another
thing to make note

01:02:20.120 --> 01:02:23.810
of, the ultimate example
of ethnic nationalism

01:02:23.810 --> 01:02:25.700
has long been considered
to be Germany,

01:02:25.700 --> 01:02:28.560
especially pre-WWII Germany.

01:02:28.560 --> 01:02:29.900
We all know where that went.

01:02:29.900 --> 01:02:31.800
It was not good.

01:02:31.800 --> 01:02:35.030
So ethnic nationalism
has a good long history

01:02:35.030 --> 01:02:38.240
of being looked at askance.

01:02:38.240 --> 01:02:40.790
I won't really have time
to go global with this.

01:02:40.790 --> 01:02:43.910
I think that this civic
versus ethnic nationalism

01:02:43.910 --> 01:02:46.500
class can explain a lot of
things around the world,

01:02:46.500 --> 01:02:49.610
including India, which I'm
happy to go into during Q&amp;A

01:02:49.610 --> 01:02:51.110
or follow up if you want.

01:02:51.110 --> 01:02:53.450
My argument is always
that, in India, we

01:02:53.450 --> 01:02:55.370
had our Trump in 2014.

01:02:55.370 --> 01:03:00.140
Right we had him 2 and 1/2 years
before we had ours in the US.

01:03:00.140 --> 01:03:03.290
India has definitely
brought to power

01:03:03.290 --> 01:03:06.800
a party that rejects a secular,
civic definition of India.

01:03:06.800 --> 01:03:11.115
It wants to resurrect an ethnic,
Hindu religious definition

01:03:11.115 --> 01:03:11.615
of India.

01:03:14.420 --> 01:03:16.559
So we're at Radcliffe.

01:03:16.559 --> 01:03:18.850
And I don't want to miss the
women in nationalism part.

01:03:18.850 --> 01:03:21.270
So I'll close with this.

01:03:21.270 --> 01:03:22.810
Feminist scholars
of nationalism,

01:03:22.810 --> 01:03:26.590
if not always the mainstream
scholars of nationalism,

01:03:26.590 --> 01:03:29.170
have long argued and understood
the critical role of gender

01:03:29.170 --> 01:03:31.360
in constructing
national identities.

01:03:31.360 --> 01:03:33.070
They've explained
how women are seen

01:03:33.070 --> 01:03:35.410
as those who
propagate the nation,

01:03:35.410 --> 01:03:38.140
both literally by
producing children,

01:03:38.140 --> 01:03:41.980
but also culturally in
passing on language and values

01:03:41.980 --> 01:03:44.890
to the next generation.

01:03:44.890 --> 01:03:48.010
Women attend to hearth
and home when men are away

01:03:48.010 --> 01:03:50.170
fighting for the nation.

01:03:50.170 --> 01:03:52.270
They're also the reason
to fight to protect

01:03:52.270 --> 01:03:55.030
the nation, protecting
the women and children.

01:03:55.030 --> 01:03:57.269
And women often symbolized
the nation itself,

01:03:57.269 --> 01:03:58.810
like some of these
images I have here

01:03:58.810 --> 01:04:05.080
with Marianna France and this
famous image of Durga in India.

01:04:05.080 --> 01:04:08.620
But to me, in the terms
we've just talked about,

01:04:08.620 --> 01:04:12.520
these symbols of the
nation and of nationalism

01:04:12.520 --> 01:04:15.760
are more linked to ethnic
forms of nationalism

01:04:15.760 --> 01:04:18.160
rather than civic.

01:04:18.160 --> 01:04:20.500
It's more ethnic
nationalism that women

01:04:20.500 --> 01:04:25.240
would play these kinds of roles
in propagating the nation.

01:04:25.240 --> 01:04:27.520
And in fact, even feminist
scholars of nationalism

01:04:27.520 --> 01:04:30.730
haven't done enough
thinking, I would

01:04:30.730 --> 01:04:34.090
say, about the role of women and
gender in civic nationalisms.

01:04:34.090 --> 01:04:37.720
Maybe that's another book to
write in the next few years.

01:04:37.720 --> 01:04:39.220
I mean, in theory,
civic nationalism

01:04:39.220 --> 01:04:42.550
should be much less
gendered, therefore,

01:04:42.550 --> 01:04:43.990
perhaps, more egalitarian--

01:04:43.990 --> 01:04:45.960
I'm not sure, I have
to think about it,

01:04:45.960 --> 01:04:49.780
we can think about it together--
than ethnic nationalism.

01:04:49.780 --> 01:04:54.100
But the idea of a retrenchment
on an ethnic form or basis

01:04:54.100 --> 01:04:58.360
for US nationalism also
goes some way, in my view,

01:04:58.360 --> 01:05:01.540
to explain something that
others have found puzzling.

01:05:01.540 --> 01:05:05.680
And that is the support of white
women in particular for Trump,

01:05:05.680 --> 01:05:09.050
and not often just the working
class white women, right?

01:05:09.050 --> 01:05:14.680
Even the more educated
and wealthier white women.

01:05:14.680 --> 01:05:17.500
Despite the many
egregious reasons there

01:05:17.500 --> 01:05:19.780
have been for women--

01:05:19.780 --> 01:05:21.134
and for anyone, in fact--

01:05:21.134 --> 01:05:23.050
where they could have
or should have abandoned

01:05:23.050 --> 01:05:26.170
their support of him, if one
takes the primary concern

01:05:26.170 --> 01:05:32.350
to be the refounding, a
reasserting, or reaffirming

01:05:32.350 --> 01:05:35.352
the ethnic basis of US
nationalism, then to me,

01:05:35.352 --> 01:05:37.060
at least, that makes
more sense that they

01:05:37.060 --> 01:05:39.700
would continue to
support him if that's

01:05:39.700 --> 01:05:43.090
what they believe he's doing.

01:05:43.090 --> 01:05:46.840
So to conclude, just a
moment to think through what

01:05:46.840 --> 01:05:48.827
all this might mean.

01:05:48.827 --> 01:05:50.410
The first thing I
would say is I'm not

01:05:50.410 --> 01:05:52.810
sure I'm trying to
make an argument

01:05:52.810 --> 01:05:56.110
about whether ethnic or civic
nationalism will sort of win

01:05:56.110 --> 01:05:57.670
out in this battle.

01:05:57.670 --> 01:06:01.690
I myself am kind of rooting
for civic nationalism

01:06:01.690 --> 01:06:04.770
to win out, not least
because it's an example I

01:06:04.770 --> 01:06:07.090
want to see succeed.

01:06:07.090 --> 01:06:08.860
I think the
possibilities for women

01:06:08.860 --> 01:06:13.120
are probably better
in civic nationalism.

01:06:13.120 --> 01:06:14.950
But to me rather,
it's more about what

01:06:14.950 --> 01:06:17.200
combination of civic
and ethnic nationalism

01:06:17.200 --> 01:06:20.110
will be left when
this is all behind us.

01:06:20.110 --> 01:06:22.660
It's about whether the
underlying fear is justified,

01:06:22.660 --> 01:06:26.200
the fear that our civic
aspects are actually

01:06:26.200 --> 01:06:29.830
built on ethnic foundations,
and that they always have been,

01:06:29.830 --> 01:06:32.070
whether it was
acknowledged or not,

01:06:32.070 --> 01:06:35.650
that if the ethnic foundation
shifts as the country becomes

01:06:35.650 --> 01:06:38.170
more diverse, will
the civic structure

01:06:38.170 --> 01:06:41.230
that we've built on it collapse?

01:06:41.230 --> 01:06:43.390
Was civic nationalism
myth all along?

01:06:43.390 --> 01:06:45.850
Can we ever have a
truly civic nationalism

01:06:45.850 --> 01:06:49.684
without that
underlying ethnic base?

01:06:49.684 --> 01:06:51.100
These, to me, are
the questions we

01:06:51.100 --> 01:06:54.910
need to watch, and think about,
and grapple with going forward.

01:06:54.910 --> 01:06:58.810
I'm not going to stand here and
pretend to have any answers.

01:06:58.810 --> 01:07:02.140
But I'm certainly interested
in watching the game

01:07:02.140 --> 01:07:05.890
and hope that the
outcome is the right one.

01:07:05.890 --> 01:07:07.390
And no matter what,
I always believe

01:07:07.390 --> 01:07:11.030
in trying to make sure we're
asking the right questions.

01:07:11.030 --> 01:07:11.928
- Thank you.

01:07:11.928 --> 01:07:14.318
[APPLAUSE]

01:07:19.100 --> 01:07:21.720
Just a word, I might point
out that in the last couple

01:07:21.720 --> 01:07:25.410
of weeks, the Parkland kids
came here from Florida.

01:07:25.410 --> 01:07:27.810
There were seven who
came to Kennedy Schools

01:07:27.810 --> 01:07:31.680
and on the of day and we had
a chance to talk to them,

01:07:31.680 --> 01:07:34.500
and ask them, and try
to figure out, how could

01:07:34.500 --> 01:07:36.930
it possibly be at
a time when there's

01:07:36.930 --> 01:07:39.774
a lot of negativity about the
millennials, and who they are,

01:07:39.774 --> 01:07:41.940
and what they represent,
and these kids come forward

01:07:41.940 --> 01:07:44.510
and they're poised, they're
articulate, they're passionate,

01:07:44.510 --> 01:07:46.260
and they understand
history, and they seem

01:07:46.260 --> 01:07:48.870
to understand our civic life.

01:07:48.870 --> 01:07:52.230
And it turns out they have
a very strong civics program

01:07:52.230 --> 01:07:53.550
at that school.

01:07:53.550 --> 01:07:56.730
And it made a difference in
terms of the civic nationalism

01:07:56.730 --> 01:07:59.970
you were just discussing.

01:07:59.970 --> 01:08:01.857
But I want to ask Joan, briefly.

01:08:01.857 --> 01:08:02.940
I have just two questions.

01:08:02.940 --> 01:08:06.930
And we're going to go to the
floor for as long as we can.

01:08:06.930 --> 01:08:10.620
Joan, I briefly asked in
beginning, what about elitism

01:08:10.620 --> 01:08:12.600
in American universities?

01:08:12.600 --> 01:08:17.460
A Pew poll found that a
stunning 40% of people

01:08:17.460 --> 01:08:21.229
think that universities
are bad for the country.

01:08:21.229 --> 01:08:22.995
Bad for the country.

01:08:22.995 --> 01:08:26.890
They're our crown jewels.

01:08:26.890 --> 01:08:28.479
So what do we do?

01:08:28.479 --> 01:08:30.900
If Larry [INAUDIBLE]
came to you and said,

01:08:30.900 --> 01:08:33.483
I'm taking over Harvard's
[INAUDIBLE],, what should I do?

01:08:33.483 --> 01:08:35.649
- Well, I'm going to give
a short answer because I'm

01:08:35.649 --> 01:08:38.600
eager to hear from the audience.

01:08:38.600 --> 01:08:41.680
I think there's been
a systematic program

01:08:41.680 --> 01:08:46.750
for several decades to undermine
American education, starting

01:08:46.750 --> 01:08:49.660
with the inner cities, but
certainly not ending there.

01:08:49.660 --> 01:08:52.779
And I think it's
been very effective.

01:08:52.779 --> 01:08:55.870
And it's been
absolutely devastating

01:08:55.870 --> 01:08:58.189
for American civic life.

01:08:58.189 --> 01:08:59.979
And I think the attack
on the universities

01:08:59.979 --> 01:09:03.950
is just the latest
version of that.

01:09:03.950 --> 01:09:07.319
- And where is that
coming from, the effort

01:09:07.319 --> 01:09:10.520
to dismantle and discredit?

01:09:10.520 --> 01:09:13.750
- I think that it is
coming from people

01:09:13.750 --> 01:09:20.930
who would prefer a passive
and uneducated electorate.

01:09:20.930 --> 01:09:22.990
As I say, I'm eager to
hear from the audience.

01:09:22.990 --> 01:09:24.010
I'm not really sure.

01:09:24.010 --> 01:09:27.670
- Let me ask the
group one question.

01:09:27.670 --> 01:09:29.470
The United States
is soon going to be

01:09:29.470 --> 01:09:33.010
a country where the
whites Caucasians are

01:09:33.010 --> 01:09:34.060
no longer the majority.

01:09:34.060 --> 01:09:37.300
We're going to have a
majority of minorities.

01:09:37.300 --> 01:09:43.390
And the central issue becomes,
can a multi ethnic society

01:09:43.390 --> 01:09:45.149
succeed?

01:09:45.149 --> 01:09:47.240
And I just would
like to ask you,

01:09:47.240 --> 01:09:48.979
is there an example
you can point to

01:09:48.979 --> 01:09:52.880
of a multi-ethnic society
that has been successful?

01:09:52.880 --> 01:09:56.990
Or what country would you point
to that's come the closest?

01:09:56.990 --> 01:09:59.840
- Well, it depends on how you
define success, doesn't it?

01:09:59.840 --> 01:10:02.540
- Well, it does.

01:10:02.540 --> 01:10:04.870
- But just to say
something, I mean,

01:10:04.870 --> 01:10:08.380
if you want to have a
post-colonial take on why is it

01:10:08.380 --> 01:10:12.640
that universities are taken
on, one can argue that we are

01:10:12.640 --> 01:10:17.080
switching from an entitlement
society to an achievement

01:10:17.080 --> 01:10:18.450
society.

01:10:18.450 --> 01:10:20.850
And then universities,
of course,

01:10:20.850 --> 01:10:23.665
are where you go when
you achieve something.

01:10:23.665 --> 01:10:26.320
Whereas, the rest,
of course, no longer

01:10:26.320 --> 01:10:31.180
have the entitlement,
which they had always

01:10:31.180 --> 01:10:35.050
thought was achievement that
came because of what they did

01:10:35.050 --> 01:10:39.330
rather than because of where
they were born and who--

01:10:39.330 --> 01:10:41.410
- Working class
families would argue

01:10:41.410 --> 01:10:43.390
that the sons and
daughters who are

01:10:43.390 --> 01:10:46.035
going to these elite
universities do feel entitled.

01:10:46.035 --> 01:10:48.160
And they're there because
they had a certain amount

01:10:48.160 --> 01:10:50.860
of entitlement in life.

01:10:50.860 --> 01:10:52.410
- Their children feel that.

01:10:52.410 --> 01:10:54.780
- Well, then others look
at it and say, well, you've

01:10:54.780 --> 01:10:56.365
got it in, you've
got a legacy, you've

01:10:56.365 --> 01:10:59.307
got all these things
that are going on.

01:10:59.307 --> 01:11:00.140
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:11:00.140 --> 01:11:01.990
- Just saying, we
did have a legacy,

01:11:01.990 --> 01:11:03.250
that's why I got into Yale.

01:11:06.240 --> 01:11:07.010
- Yeah.

01:11:07.010 --> 01:11:09.330
- But again, let's go
back to this question.

01:11:09.330 --> 01:11:11.560
Can multi-ethnic societies work?

01:11:11.560 --> 01:11:15.680
Which ones are
coming the closest?

01:11:15.680 --> 01:11:18.460
- One thing, when
you say multi-ethnic,

01:11:18.460 --> 01:11:22.600
you assume that all ethnicities
are equal to each other.

01:11:22.600 --> 01:11:24.110
And they are not.

01:11:24.110 --> 01:11:27.640
multi-ethnic means that,
because of history, because

01:11:27.640 --> 01:11:30.310
of intersectionality,
with power,

01:11:30.310 --> 01:11:34.900
some ethnicities are always
more privileged than other ones.

01:11:34.900 --> 01:11:37.000
If you bring them
together, then,

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:39.880
you cannot assume that
they are all the same.

01:11:39.880 --> 01:11:44.310
- Given that, how do countries
overcome the challenge, please?

01:11:44.310 --> 01:11:50.120
- I wonder if I could ask a
question in return which is,

01:11:50.120 --> 01:11:53.270
which society has not
been multi-ethnic?

01:11:53.270 --> 01:11:57.170
Right the myth one can
have a majority ethnicity,

01:11:57.170 --> 01:12:00.820
but I think anything but
a multi-ethnic society

01:12:00.820 --> 01:12:04.330
at some level is not
a fully real thing.

01:12:04.330 --> 01:12:06.590
- Go back to the
fundamental argument

01:12:06.590 --> 01:12:09.190
underlying all of this, that
many people no longer feel

01:12:09.190 --> 01:12:11.140
at home, and a lot
of those people

01:12:11.140 --> 01:12:12.930
are coming from the
majority who now

01:12:12.930 --> 01:12:14.935
feel like they're
turning into the minority

01:12:14.935 --> 01:12:16.810
and are being
overwhelmed by others who

01:12:16.810 --> 01:12:18.480
are coming in from the outside.

01:12:18.480 --> 01:12:22.810
- In the US, there is this
kind of new theorizing

01:12:22.810 --> 01:12:26.860
in terms of super diversity,
that all countries,

01:12:26.860 --> 01:12:30.130
many countries, many cities
become minority majorities.

01:12:30.130 --> 01:12:33.920
So indeed, the white mainstream
will then be disappearing.

01:12:33.920 --> 01:12:36.040
And I agree with you.

01:12:36.040 --> 01:12:39.190
This suggestion that it's
