01:33:52.440 --> 01:33:56.400
I do want to offer just a
quick set of concluding remarks

01:33:56.400 --> 01:33:59.820
because Liz told me to.

01:33:59.820 --> 01:34:01.630
Who belongs?

01:34:01.630 --> 01:34:04.560
This is a quotidien call.

01:34:04.560 --> 01:34:09.690
It is answered every day,
as is the question posed,

01:34:09.690 --> 01:34:12.300
by institutions
and rules that are

01:34:12.300 --> 01:34:15.090
every bit of a part
of our fabric and life

01:34:15.090 --> 01:34:18.150
but are often less visible,
sometimes entirely invisible.

01:34:18.150 --> 01:34:21.510
So I want to focus on two
categories, written rules

01:34:21.510 --> 01:34:23.940
and unwritten
rules, if you will.

01:34:23.940 --> 01:34:26.790
We heard about written
rules in the world

01:34:26.790 --> 01:34:29.010
of birthright citizenship.

01:34:29.010 --> 01:34:31.540
We heard about how
structures of law,

01:34:31.540 --> 01:34:33.560
particularly
birthright citizenship,

01:34:33.560 --> 01:34:35.520
converts the state
into something

01:34:35.520 --> 01:34:38.280
of an emperor of whim,
of chance, of just, where

01:34:38.280 --> 01:34:40.710
did you happen to
be born, and then

01:34:40.710 --> 01:34:42.480
converting that
into your status,

01:34:42.480 --> 01:34:44.940
your identity, your resources.

01:34:44.940 --> 01:34:48.240
We heard Martha Jones talk about
the limited and discretionary

01:34:48.240 --> 01:34:51.180
ways in which birthright
citizenship was applied

01:34:51.180 --> 01:34:53.400
and extended in her
wonderful metaphor,

01:34:53.400 --> 01:34:57.630
birthright citizenship as the
haven and the scythe at once.

01:34:57.630 --> 01:34:59.820
We heard Sarah Leah
Whitson describe

01:34:59.820 --> 01:35:04.350
about how, in Jordan, Jordanian
birthright citizenship was

01:35:04.350 --> 01:35:06.520
linked to Jordanian
fatherhood, but not

01:35:06.520 --> 01:35:09.120
the Jordanian motherhood
or to the children

01:35:09.120 --> 01:35:13.050
of Jordanian mothers
without Jordanian fathers.

01:35:13.050 --> 01:35:15.000
And it's worth remembering
that the birther

01:35:15.000 --> 01:35:19.900
movement, or that meme,
for a while, linked

01:35:19.900 --> 01:35:22.230
to a different kind
of citizenship, one

01:35:22.230 --> 01:35:25.050
actually not connected
to the 14th Amendment,

01:35:25.050 --> 01:35:27.810
but connected to article
two of our constitution,

01:35:27.810 --> 01:35:29.850
the original
Constitution, and the way

01:35:29.850 --> 01:35:34.080
that it defines eligibility
for our presidency.

01:35:34.080 --> 01:35:36.810
We also talked about
immigration structures.

01:35:36.810 --> 01:35:38.580
Immigration judges
of the sort that

01:35:38.580 --> 01:35:42.690
were talked about by Professor
Carey Huang of Boston College

01:35:42.690 --> 01:35:43.777
Law School.

01:35:43.777 --> 01:35:45.360
And it's interesting
that those judges

01:35:45.360 --> 01:35:48.990
are answerable to and
employed by not the Supreme

01:35:48.990 --> 01:35:52.890
Court, the judicial branch, but
by the executive branch, which

01:35:52.890 --> 01:35:54.930
is one reason that they
are subject to some

01:35:54.930 --> 01:35:59.100
of the directives of
Attorney General Sessions

01:35:59.100 --> 01:36:01.740
and of President Trump,
which means at some level

01:36:01.740 --> 01:36:04.770
that the access to an
independent judiciary

01:36:04.770 --> 01:36:09.625
in our country is itself
conditioned upon citizenship.

01:36:09.625 --> 01:36:11.750
And as another way of
thinking about written rules,

01:36:11.750 --> 01:36:14.360
we heard about the really
interesting research of Tali

01:36:14.360 --> 01:36:18.050
Mendelberg, and the way in
which even a voting rule, which

01:36:18.050 --> 01:36:20.660
is to say, what's the threshold
that determines by which

01:36:20.660 --> 01:36:24.650
something gets passed or failed
in a vote, majority, or simply

01:36:24.650 --> 01:36:26.600
unanimity, but the
way that affects

01:36:26.600 --> 01:36:28.340
the way people participate.

01:36:28.340 --> 01:36:32.300
So the written rules are
there with us everywhere.

01:36:32.300 --> 01:36:35.480
But I think rules
are often sometimes

01:36:35.480 --> 01:36:37.910
most powerful when
they're implicit,

01:36:37.910 --> 01:36:40.550
when they're unwritten,
and when they're assumed.

01:36:40.550 --> 01:36:43.370
I have a friend, an
African-American man

01:36:43.370 --> 01:36:45.170
I've known for a long
time, a good friend.

01:36:45.170 --> 01:36:46.585
He's a PhD psychologist.

01:36:46.585 --> 01:36:48.960
He told me something recently
that kind of stuck with me.

01:36:48.960 --> 01:36:51.335
He said, well, when you hear
about the canary in the coal

01:36:51.335 --> 01:36:55.324
mine, the important
point when you're

01:36:55.324 --> 01:36:57.740
hearing about that metaphor
of the canary in the coal mine

01:36:57.740 --> 01:37:00.500
isn't about the canary.

01:37:00.500 --> 01:37:01.640
It's about the context.

01:37:01.640 --> 01:37:04.940
It's about the gaseous
threats that are

01:37:04.940 --> 01:37:06.337
emerging from the coal mine.

01:37:06.337 --> 01:37:08.420
And so the point isn't
really about the thing that

01:37:08.420 --> 01:37:10.010
keels over and stops chirping.

01:37:10.010 --> 01:37:13.010
It's about the context.

01:37:13.010 --> 01:37:16.460
And that invisible context, I
think, is with us everywhere.

01:37:16.460 --> 01:37:19.430
To get back to, for instance,
Tali Mendelberg's idea

01:37:19.430 --> 01:37:22.337
of just the number of people
in the room who are women.

01:37:22.337 --> 01:37:24.170
You know, a lot of the
experimental subjects

01:37:24.170 --> 01:37:26.336
probably didn't know that,
oh, look, it's all women,

01:37:26.336 --> 01:37:28.970
or it's 80% women as
opposed to 20% women.

01:37:28.970 --> 01:37:31.130
Yet, that invisible
fact structured

01:37:31.130 --> 01:37:32.960
the way they treated
others and the way

01:37:32.960 --> 01:37:34.845
they rated them is influential.

01:37:34.845 --> 01:37:39.650
You can think about Fatma Muge
Gogek's point about, well,

01:37:39.650 --> 01:37:43.550
does everybody just have one
identity, just one nationality?

01:37:43.550 --> 01:37:47.000
That's a common assumption
that we all make.

01:37:47.000 --> 01:37:52.880
Or Joan Williams', I think, very
thoughtful, poignant criticism,

01:37:52.880 --> 01:37:56.610
have working class people of
whatever race in this country,

01:37:56.610 --> 01:37:59.510
in the United States, been
stripped of a certain degree

01:37:59.510 --> 01:38:02.900
of cultural citizenship or
of educational citizenship?

01:38:02.900 --> 01:38:04.790
Have they been
assumed irredeemable

01:38:04.790 --> 01:38:06.980
based on where they live?

01:38:06.980 --> 01:38:11.210
I note as somebody who grew up
in a small town in the Midwest,

01:38:11.210 --> 01:38:15.800
that that is not merely a
simple, white racial fact

01:38:15.800 --> 01:38:16.880
that she's pointing to.

01:38:16.880 --> 01:38:19.460
There were many Native
American reservations

01:38:19.460 --> 01:38:24.530
that went from 60/40 Obama
Romney to 60/40 Trump

01:38:24.530 --> 01:38:26.720
Clinton for some of
the same reasons,

01:38:26.720 --> 01:38:29.897
namely, that their economies had
been wrecked in recent years.

01:38:29.897 --> 01:38:31.730
Does that mean that
dynamics are not racial?

01:38:31.730 --> 01:38:32.690
Of course not.

01:38:32.690 --> 01:38:34.850
Does that mean they're
deeply involved with class

01:38:34.850 --> 01:38:36.530
and economic trajectories?

01:38:36.530 --> 01:38:38.770
Yes, it does.

01:38:38.770 --> 01:38:41.890
We heard Nulifer
Gole's discussion

01:38:41.890 --> 01:38:44.740
of Muslim women in
Europe, especially France,

01:38:44.740 --> 01:38:49.510
and the idea of the burkini,
and her asking this question of,

01:38:49.510 --> 01:38:53.770
does belonging entail the
subjugation of our identities

01:38:53.770 --> 01:38:55.120
for some people?

01:38:55.120 --> 01:39:01.030
For instance, of the idea of the
corporeal person or personhood,

01:39:01.030 --> 01:39:04.480
and how people, especially
Muslim women, treat,

01:39:04.480 --> 01:39:07.450
cover, and display
their own bodies?

01:39:07.450 --> 01:39:11.690
Or think of the father in
Jhumpa Lahiri's beautiful story,

01:39:11.690 --> 01:39:15.610
Il Confine, The
Boundary, that father

01:39:15.610 --> 01:39:18.260
who had retreated to the
countryside, who, in a sense,

01:39:18.260 --> 01:39:22.630
had exiled himself from his
own nation, his new nation,

01:39:22.630 --> 01:39:24.760
living away from the
city so he didn't

01:39:24.760 --> 01:39:27.670
have to expose his
shattered teeth,

01:39:27.670 --> 01:39:30.790
so he didn't have to
expose his infacility

01:39:30.790 --> 01:39:34.660
with the official tongue.

01:39:34.660 --> 01:39:38.440
So who belongs strikes me as the
fundamental political question

01:39:38.440 --> 01:39:39.910
of our time.

01:39:39.910 --> 01:39:43.750
And our answers often
come in the form

01:39:43.750 --> 01:39:46.480
of borders, not merely
concrete borders,

01:39:46.480 --> 01:39:47.860
but categorical borders.

01:39:47.860 --> 01:39:49.870
And those borders can be fluid.

01:39:49.870 --> 01:39:51.520
They can be paraffine.

01:39:51.520 --> 01:39:54.910
They can be cemented
in a Trumpian fantasy

01:39:54.910 --> 01:39:56.740
and built very high.

01:39:56.740 --> 01:39:58.990
But those borders are
always constructed,

01:39:58.990 --> 01:40:02.140
even if the president
wishes to construct them.

01:40:02.140 --> 01:40:05.830
But that means not just that the
cement borders are constructed,

01:40:05.830 --> 01:40:07.480
but so are the categorical ones.

01:40:07.480 --> 01:40:10.450
And so, to get back to one of
the calls from one of our very

01:40:10.450 --> 01:40:14.200
first speakers today, professor
Kerry Kari Hong, maybe we,

01:40:14.200 --> 01:40:18.280
in part, start changing those
borders by changing our talk,

01:40:18.280 --> 01:40:20.740
by changing the
talk, including--

01:40:20.740 --> 01:40:22.930
to get back to Joan Williams--

01:40:22.930 --> 01:40:26.260
the talk that we regularly
and assumably carry

01:40:26.260 --> 01:40:27.760
on in our universities.

01:40:27.760 --> 01:40:29.560
And I'll conclude there.

01:40:29.560 --> 01:40:32.310
[APPLAUSE]

